SIMPLE: trample
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trample
<hw>Tram"ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trampled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Trampling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trampelen</ets>, freq. of <ets>trampen</ets>. See <er>Tramp</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tread under foot; to tread
down; to prostrate by treading; <as>as, to <ex>trample</ex> grass or
flowers</as>.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither cast ye your pearls before swine, lest they
<qex>trample</qex> them under their feet.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vii.
6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To treat with contempt and insult.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trample</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trample
<hw>Tram"ple</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tread with force
and rapidity; to stamp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To tread in contempt; -- with <xex>on</xex> or
<xex>upon</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Diogenes <qex>trampled</qex> on Plato's pride with greater of his
own.</q> <rj><qau>Gov. of Tongue.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trample</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trample
<hw>Tram"ple</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of treading under foot;
also, the sound produced by trampling.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The huddling <qex>trample</qex> of a drove of sheep.</q>
<rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trampler</ent>⟦br⟧
